'''Bovine spongiform encephalopathy''' ('''BSE'''), commonly known as '''mad cow disease''', is a fatal [[neurodegenerative disease]] ([[encephalopathy]]) in [[cattle]] that causes a spongy degeneration in the [[brain]] and [[spinal cord]]. BSE has a long [[incubation period]], about 30 months to 8 years, usually affecting adult cattle at a peak age onset of four to five years, all [[breed]]s being equally susceptible.<ref name="FSRIO">
{{cite web
 | title = A Focus on Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy
 | url = http://fsrio.nal.usda.gov/document_fsheet.php?product_id=169
 | accessdate = 2008-04-07
 | year = 2007
 | month = November
 | work = Pathogens and Contaminants
 | publisher = Food Safety Research Information Office
|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080303135425/http://fsrio.nal.usda.gov/document_fsheet.php?product_id=169 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 3 March 2008}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom]], the country worst affected, more than 180,000 cattle have been infected and 4.4 million slaughtered during the eradication program.<ref name="Brown">
{{cite news
 | title = The 'recipe for disaster' that killed 80 and left a £5bn bill
 | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1371964/The-recipe-for-disaster-that-killed-80-and-left-a-5bn-bill.html
 | accessdate = 2008-04-07
 | last = Brown
 | first = David
 | date = 19 June 2001
 |work=The Daily Telegraph
| location=London
}}</ref>

The disease may be most easily transmitted to [[human beings]] by eating food contaminated with the brain, spinal cord or digestive tract of infected carcasses.<ref name="FDA/CFSAN">
