A British and Irish inquiry into BSE concluded the [[epizootic]] was caused by cattle, which are normally [[herbivore]]s, being fed the remains of other cattle in the form of [[meat and bone meal]] (MBM), which caused the infectious agent to spread.<ref name="DEFRA/BSE">{{ cite web | url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/bse/controls-eradication/causes.html | title=BSE: Disease control & eradication – Causes of BSE | publisher=Department for Environment, Food, and Rural Affairs | date=March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bseinquiry.gov.uk/ | title=The BSE Inquiry}}</ref> The cause of BSE may be from the contamination of MBM from sheep with [[scrapie]] that were processed in the same slaughterhouse. The epidemic was probably accelerated by the recycling of infected bovine tissues prior to the recognition of BSE.<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9169904 | title=Bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE): causes and consequences of a common source epidemic | last1=Nathanson |first1=N |last2=Wilesmith |first2=J |last3=Griot |first3=C| date=June 1997}}</ref> The origin of the disease itself remains unknown. The infectious agent is distinctive for the high temperatures at which it remains viable, over 600 degrees [[Celsius]]<ref>{{cite news
